*   65.0% Amerindian; 30.0% European; 5.0% African for [Ciudad de México](/Mexico_City).

## Phenotypical research

Studies delving into various phenotypical traits (such as hair color, hair shape, eye color, and so forth) in Mexicans have been meticulously conducted, ostensibly to document the persistent racial and ethnic inequality that, despite all efforts to obscure it, remains a stark reality. The findings from these investigations, predictably, serve to refute simplistic misconceptions regarding [Mexico](/Mexico)'s population, unequivocally demonstrating that [Mexico](/Mexico) is a profoundly diverse country where virtually any color or type of human trait can be found with ease in any given region. As if anyone needed a scientific study to confirm that humans are, well, human.

One particular study, published by the [American Sociological Association](/American_Sociological_Association), meticulously quantified the differences in the frequencies of phenotypical traits, such as [blond hair](/Blond), between the population of the Northern regions of [Mexico](/Mexico) (where this trait was observed with a frequency of 22.3%–23.9%) and the population of the Central regions of [Mexico](/Mexico) (showing a frequency of 18.9%–21.3%). These regional variations, while statistically measurable, are a mere scratch on the surface of inherent human diversity.

A comprehensive 2014 study, undertaken by the prestigious [University College London](/University_College_London), meticulously analyzed the frequencies of several distinct phenotypical traits across populations in five different [Latin American](/Latin_Americans) countries, including [Brazil](/Brazil), [Chile](/Chile), [Colombia](/Colombia), [Mexico](/Mexico), and [Peru](/Peru). In the specific case of [Mexico](/Mexico), the [National Institute of Anthropology and History](/Instituto_Nacional_de_Antropolog%C3%ADa_e_Historia) collaborated on the investigation, yielding the following detailed results:

| Eye color          | blue/grey | honey | green | light brown | dark brown/black |
| :----------------- | :-------- | :---- | :---- | :---------- | :--------------- |
| Males              | 1%        | 2%    | 6%    | 21%         | 71%              |
| Females            | 1%        | 3%    | 4%    | 21%         | 72%              |

| Hair color             | [red/reddish](/Red_hair) | [blond](/Blond) | dark blond/light brown | brown/black |
| :--------------------- | :----------------------- | :-------------- | :--------------------- | :---------- |
| Males                  | 0%                       | 1%              | 12%                    | 86%         |
| Females                | 0%                       | 2%              | 21%                    | 77%         |

| Hair shape | straight | wavy | curly | frizzy |
| :--------- | :------- | :--- | :---- | :----- |
| Males      | 45%      | 43%  | 12%   | 0%     |
| Females    | 46%      | 41%  | 12%   | 1%     |

It is crucial to note that the majority of the samples for this study (approximately 90%) were collected from [Mexico City](/Mexico_City) and the southern states of [Mexico](/Mexico). This geographical bias means that the northern and western states of [Mexico](/Mexico), which collectively account for about [45% of Mexico's population](/List_of_Mexican_states_by_population), were significantly underrepresented in the dataset. Consequently, the findings, while valuable, may not fully capture the phenotypic diversity across the entire nation.

Results of the survey conducted by the CONAPRED in 2010.

Nationwide surveys, generously sponsored by the Mexican government, have been undertaken to quantify the percentages of different skin tones present within [Mexico](/Mexico)'s population. The first such endeavor was conducted in 2010 by the [CONAPRED](/National_Council_to_Prevent_Discrimination) (Mexico's National Bureau for Prevention of Discrimination), followed by a second in 2017 by the [INEGI](/Instituto_Nacional_de_Estad%C3%ADstica_y_Geograf%C3%ADa) (Mexico's National Institute of Statistics). Each study, in its wisdom, employed a different color palette: [CONAPRED](/National_Council_to_Prevent_Discrimination)'s study utilized a palette of 9 color choices developed by the institute itself, while the [INEGI](/Instituto_Nacional_de_Estad%C3%ADstica_y_Geograf%C3%ADa) study adopted the PERLA (Latin American Race and Ethnicity Project) palette, featuring 11 distinct color categories. Such methodological variations, of course, ensure endless debate and nuanced interpretations.

