According to data from the [Mexican Social Security Institute](/Mexican_Social_Security_Institute) (IMSS), approximately half of all Mexican babies nationwide are born with the distinctive [Mongolian spot](/Mongolian_spot) birthmark. This common dermatological feature, a benign, flat, bluish-gray or blue-black birthmark, is particularly prevalent among infants of East Asian, Southeast Asian, Indigenous American, and African descent, further illustrating the deep and varied genetic heritage present within the Mexican population.

## Languages

*   Main articles: [Languages of Mexico](/Languages_of_Mexico) and [Mexican Spanish](/Mexican_Spanish)

Map for the year 2000 of the indigenous languages of Mexico having more than 100,000 speakers

Mexicans, as a collective, exhibit a remarkable linguistic diversity, a testament to centuries of cultural convergence and divergence. While a vast majority, approximately 92.17% of Mexicans, speak [Spanish](/Mexican_Spanish) as their first language—making them the largest Spanish-speaking group globally, surpassing [Colombia](/Colombia) (45,273,925), [Spain](/Spain) (41,063,259), and [Argentina](/Argentina) (40,134,425)—a rich mosaic of various [Indigenous Mexican Languages](/Mesoamerican_languages) also thrives. The most widely spoken indigenous language among Mexicans is [Nahuatl](/Nahuatl), which is spoken by 1.7% of the population aged 5 and above. According to the 2020 Mexican Census, an estimated 7,364,645 Mexicans, constituting 6.1% of the total population, speak an indigenous language. While the exact number remains elusive, many Mexicans residing abroad, particularly in the [United States](/United_States), also continue to speak indigenous languages, maintaining their linguistic heritage across borders. Although [Spanish](/Mexican_Spanish) is overwhelmingly dominant, the second most populous language among Mexicans is, perhaps unsurprisingly, [English](/English_language). This prevalence is largely due to the geographical proximity to the [United States](/United_States), which necessitates a bilingual relationship for robust business and trade, as well as the significant migration of Mexicans into that country, where many adopt English as a second language for integration and opportunity.

[Mexican Spanish](/Mexican_Spanish) stands as a distinct dialect, characterized by unique tones, syntax, and vocabulary that differentiate it from the [Peninsular Spanish](/Peninsular_Spanish) spoken in [Spain](/Spain). This divergence is partly due to its rich linguistic borrowing from indigenous languages. It proudly incorporates a substantial number of loan words, predominantly from the [Nahuatl](/Nahuatl) language, which have become integral to everyday speech. Examples include "chocolate," "tomate" (tomato), "mezquite" (mesquite tree), "chile," and "coyote," demonstrating the deep and lasting indigenous influence on the national tongue.

[Mexico](/Mexico) holds the distinction of having no official *de jure* language, a decision that, in 2003, formally recognized 68 indigenous Amerindian languages as "national languages" alongside [Spanish](/Spanish_language). This groundbreaking legislation provides crucial protection under Mexican National law, granting indigenous peoples the undeniable entitlement to request public services and official documents in their native languages. The law's progressive scope extends even further, encompassing other Amerindian languages regardless of their origin, meaning it includes indigenous languages spoken by ethnic groups not originally native to Mexican national territory. Consequently, [Mexico](/Mexico)'s [National Commission for the Development of Indigenous Peoples](/National_Commission_for_the_Development_of_Indigenous_Peoples) officially recognizes, for instance, the language of the [Kickapoo](/Kickapoo_people) people, who immigrated from the [United States](/United_States), and also extends recognition to the languages spoken by [Guatemalan](/Guatemala) Amerindian refugees, highlighting a truly inclusive approach to linguistic heritage.

## Culture

*   Main article: [Culture of Mexico](/Culture_of_Mexico)

View of [Zócalo](/Z%C3%B3calo), Mexico City

Mexican culture is a vibrant, intricate tapestry that vividly reflects the profound complexity of the [country's history](/History_of_Mexico). It is a remarkable blend, a deep synthesis of indigenous cultures, which represent millennia of distinct traditions, and the [culture of Spain](/Culture_of_Spain), meticulously imparted and enforced during [Spain](/Spain)'s extensive 300-year colonization of [Mexico](/Mexico). Beyond these foundational influences, exogenous cultural elements, primarily emanating from the [United States](/United_States) due to geographical proximity and economic ties, have also been seamlessly, or sometimes jarringly, incorporated into the broader Mexican cultural landscape.

The [Porfirian era](/Porfirio_D%C3%ADaz) (el [Porfiriato](/Porfirio_D%C3%ADaz)), spanning the final quarter of the 19th century and the initial decade of the 20th century, was paradoxically characterized by both authoritarian rule and significant economic progress, alongside a period of relative peace after decades of internal strife. During this time, after four tumultuous decades of civil unrest and war, [Mexico](/Mexico) experienced a notable flourishing of philosophy and the arts, cultural endeavors actively promoted by President Díaz himself, perhaps to project an image of stability and modernity. Since that era, and particularly accentuated during the seismic shifts of the [Mexican Revolution](/Mexican_Revolution), cultural identity has increasingly found its bedrock in the concept of [mestizaje](/Mestizos), where the indigenous (i.e., Amerindian) element is often championed as the very core. In light of the diverse array of ethnicities that coalesced to form the Mexican people, the influential intellectual [José Vasconcelos](/Jos%C3%A9_Vasconcelos), in his seminal publication *[La Raza Cósmica](/La_Raza_C%C3%B3smica)* (The Cosmic Race) in 1925, articulated a vision of [Mexico](/Mexico) as the ultimate "melting pot" of all races. This expansive definition extended the concept of the [mestizo](/Mestizos) beyond mere biology to encompass a profound cultural synthesis. This exalting of [mestizaje](/Mestizos) was a truly revolutionary idea for its time, sharply contrasting with the prevalent, often nationalistic, notions of a superior "pure race" that dominated intellectual discourse in [Europe](/Europe) during the early 20th century.

### Literature

*   Main articles: [Mexican literature](/Mexican_literature) and [Mesoamerican literature](/Mesoamerican_literature)

[Casa del Lago Juan José Arreola](/Casa_del_Lago_Juan_Jos%C3%A9_Arreola) [Cultural Center](/Cultural_Center) of the [National Autonomous University of Mexico](/National_Autonomous_University_of_Mexico).

The rich tapestry of literature in [Mexico](/Mexico) boasts deep antecedents in the sophisticated literatures of the indigenous settlements that flourished across [Mesoamerica](/Mesoamerica). Among the most celebrated prehispanic poets, the revered figure of [Nezahualcoyotl](/Nezahualcoyotl_(tlatoani)), the wise ruler of Texcoco, stands prominent, his verses offering profound insights into Aztec cosmology and human experience. Modern Mexican literature, in its subsequent development, was profoundly shaped and influenced by the complex concepts and realities introduced through the Spanish colonialization of [Mesoamerica](/Mesoamerica). Outstanding writers and poets from this Spanish colonial period include the dramatist [Juan Ruiz de Alarcón](/Juan_Ruiz_de_Alarc%C3%B3n), known for his sharp wit and intricate plots, and the brilliant nun, scholar, and poet [Juana Inés de la Cruz](/Juana_In%C3%A9s_de_la_Cruz), whose intellectual prowess and poetic genius defied the societal constraints of her era.

As previously mentioned, in light of the complex and varied ethnicities that contributed to the formation of the Mexican people, the influential philosopher and educator [José Vasconcelos](/Jos%C3%A9_Vasconcelos), in his groundbreaking publication *[La Raza Cósmica](/La_Raza_C%C3%B3smica)* (The Cosmic Race) in 1925, articulated a compelling vision. He defined [Mexico](/Mexico) not merely as a biological fusion, but as a dynamic "melting pot" of all races, extending the concept of the [mestizo](/Mestizos) to encompass a profound and inclusive cultural synthesis.

Beyond these foundational figures, the pantheon of Mexican literary giants includes luminaries such as [Alfonso Reyes](/Alfonso_Reyes), a prodigious essayist and poet; [José Joaquín Fernández de Lizardi](/Jos%C3%A9_Joaqu%C3%ADn_Fern%C3%A1ndez_de_Lizardi), often credited with writing the first Latin American novel; and [Ignacio Manuel Altamirano](/Ignacio_Manuel_Altamirano), a key figure in 19th-century Mexican romanticism. More contemporary masters include [Carlos Fuentes](/Carlos_Fuentes), a towering figure of the Latin American Boom; [Octavio Paz](/Octavio_Paz), a Nobel Laureate whose poetry and essays explored themes of identity and existentialism; [Renato Leduc](/Renato_Leduc), celebrated for his irreverent wit; [Carlos Monsiváis](/Carlos_Monsiv%C3%A1is), a keen observer of Mexican popular culture; and [Elena Poniatowska](/Elena_Poniatowska), a prolific journalist and novelist known for her social commentary. The revolutionary literary tradition is represented by [Mariano Azuela](/Mariano_Azuela), author of *Los de abajo*, a seminal novel of the [Mexican Revolution](/Mexican_Revolution), and the enigmatic [Juan Rulfo](/Juan_Rulfo), whose masterpiece *Pedro Páramo* profoundly influenced magical realism. Even the mysterious [Bruno Traven](/Bruno_Traven), whose true identity remains debated, contributed significantly with works like *Canasta de cuentos mexicanos* and *El tesoro de la Sierra Madre* (The Treasure of the Sierra Madre), further enriching the diverse landscape of Mexican storytelling.

### Science

*   Main article: [History of science and technology in Mexico](/History_of_science_and_technology_in_Mexico)

The [National Autonomous University of Mexico](/National_Autonomous_University_of_Mexico) (UNAM) was officially established in 1910, a pivotal moment that cemented its status as one of the most significant and influential institutions of higher learning in [Mexico](/Mexico). From its inception, UNAM has consistently provided world-class education across critical fields such as science, medicine, and engineering, becoming a beacon of intellectual development. The first half of the 20th century witnessed a significant proliferation of scientific institutes and new establishments dedicated to higher learning, including the founding of the [National Polytechnic Institute](/National_Polytechnic_Institute) in 1936. Many of these newly created research institutes were strategically integrated within the broader framework of UNAM itself, with twelve institutes becoming part of the university between 1929 and 1973, fostering a centralized hub of scientific inquiry. In 1959, the [Mexican Academy of Sciences](/Mexican_Academy_of_Sciences) was established, specifically tasked with coordinating and promoting scientific efforts among academics nationwide.

A crowning achievement in Mexican science occurred in 1995 when the distinguished Mexican chemist [Mario J. Molina](/Mario_J._Molina) was jointly awarded the [Nobel Prize in Chemistry](/Nobel_Prize_in_Chemistry) with [Paul J. Crutzen](/Paul_J._Crutzen) and [F. Sherwood Rowland](/F._Sherwood_Rowland). Their groundbreaking work in atmospheric chemistry, particularly their crucial discoveries concerning the formation and decomposition of ozone, revolutionized our understanding of Earth's protective layer. Molina, an esteemed alumnus of UNAM, thus became the first Mexican citizen to achieve the prestigious Nobel Prize in a scientific discipline.

In more recent years, one of the most ambitious and significant scientific projects undertaken in [Mexico](/Mexico) has been the construction of the [Large Millimeter Telescope](/Large_Millimeter_Telescope) (Gran Telescopio Milimétrico, GMT). This impressive instrument holds the distinction of being the world's largest and most sensitive single-aperture telescope within its specific frequency range. Its primary design objective is to observe regions of space that are typically obscured by dense stellar dust, promising to unveil new insights into star formation, galaxy evolution, and the early universe.

### Music

*   Main article: [Music of Mexico](/Music_of_Mexico)
*   See also: [List of Mexican composers of classical music](/List_of_Mexican_composers_of_classical_music)

Mexican society embraces a vast and vibrant array of music genres, a sonic reflection of the profound diversity embedded within Mexican culture itself. Traditional music forms a rich bedrock, encompassing iconic styles such as [mariachi](/Mariachi), with its festive trumpets and violins; the lively, brass-heavy sound of [banda](/Banda_music); the accordion-driven rhythms of [Norteño](/Norte%C3%B1o_(music)); the passionate vocal storytelling of [ranchera](/Ranchera); the infectious danceability of [Mexican cumbia](/Mexican_cumbia); and the narrative ballads known as [corridos](/Corrido). On an everyday basis, however, most Mexicans readily consume contemporary music, ranging from [pop](/Mexican_pop_music) to rock, often in both English and Spanish, mirroring global trends while retaining a distinctive local flavor. [Mexico](/Mexico) boasts the largest media industry in [Hispanic America](/Hispanic_America), a powerhouse that consistently produces Mexican artists who achieve widespread fame not only across [Central](/Central_America) and [South America](/South_America) but also in various parts of [Europe](/Europe), particularly [Spain](/Spain).

Among the pantheon of well-known Mexican singers are global icons like [Thalía](/Thal%C3%ADa), the enduring romantic voice of [Luis Miguel](/Luis_Miguel), the charismatic mariachi inheritor [Alejandro Fernández](/Alejandro_Fern%C3%A1ndez), the indie-pop sensibility of [Julieta Venegas](/Julieta_Venegas), and the energetic pop star [Paulina Rubio](/Paulina_Rubio). For those who champion traditional music, the voices of [Lila Downs](/Lila_Downs), [Susana Harp](/Susana_Harp), [Jaramar](/Jaramar), [GEO Meneses](/GEO_Meneses), and [Alejandra Robles](/Alejandra_Robles) offer powerful and authentic interpretations of regional sounds. Popular groups that have captivated audiences include the eclectic [Café Tacuba](/Caf%C3%A9_Tacuba), the politically charged [Molotov](/Molotov_(band)), the pop phenomenon [RBD](/RBD), and the enduring rock band [Maná](/Man%C3%A1), among many others. Since the early years of the 2000s, [Mexican rock](/Mexican_rock) has experienced a significant and sustained period of widespread growth, both domestically within [Mexico](/Mexico) and internationally, solidifying its place on the global music stage.

### Cinema

*   Main article: [Cinema of Mexico](/Cinema_of_Mexico)

[Mexican films](/Cinema_of_Mexico) produced during the illustrious [Golden Age of Mexican cinema](/Golden_Age_of_Mexican_cinema) in the 1940s and 1950s stand as some of the most exemplary achievements in [Hispanic American](/Hispanic_America) cinema. This era saw the emergence of a colossal film industry in [Mexico](/Mexico), one that was remarkably comparable in scale and output to the Hollywood of those very same years. Mexican films from this period were not merely confined to domestic screens; they were widely exported and exhibited across all of [Hispanic America](/Hispanic_America) and significantly in [Europe](/Europe), spreading Mexican culture and storytelling far and wide. *[María Candelaria](/Mar%C3%ADa_Candelaria)* (1944), a poignant film directed by [Emilio Fernández](/Emilio_Fern%C3%A1ndez), holds the distinction of being one of the first films to be awarded a [Palme d'Or](/Palme_d%27Or) at the prestigious [Cannes Film Festival](/Cannes_Film_Festival) in 1946, marking the event's inaugural return after the devastation of World War II. The renowned Spanish-born director [Luis Buñuel](/Luis_Bu%C3%B1uel), a master of surrealism, found a fertile creative ground in [Mexico](/Mexico), where between 1947 and 1965 he realized some of his most enduring masterpieces, including *[Los Olvidados](/Los_Olvidados)* (1949), a stark portrayal of street children, the controversial *[Viridiana](/Viridiana)* (1961), and the darkly satirical *[El angel exterminador](/El_angel_exterminador)* (1963). This era was also defined by its constellation of famous actors and actresses, including the legendary screen siren [María Félix](/Mar%C3%ADa_F%C3%A9lix), the beloved idol [Pedro Infante](/Pedro_Infante), the elegant [Dolores del Río](/Dolores_del_R%C3%ADo), the dashing charro singer [Jorge Negrete](/Jorge_Negrete), and the iconic comedian [Cantinflas](/Cantinflas), whose unique brand of humor transcended borders.

In more recent times, Mexican cinema has continued its international acclaim with films such as *[Como agua para chocolate](/Like_Water_for_Chocolate_(film))* (1992), a romantic magical realist tale; [Guillermo del Toro](/Guillermo_del_Toro)'s early horror gem *[Cronos](/Cronos_(film))*(1993); the provocative road trip drama *[Y tu mamá también](/Y_tu_mam%C3%A1_también)* (2001); and the critically acclaimed dark fantasy *[Pan's Labyrinth](/Pan%27s_Labyrinth)* (2006). These films have successfully crafted universal stories exploring contemporary subjects, garnering significant international recognition, including accolades at prestigious events like the [Cannes Film Festival](/Cannes_Film_Festival). Today, Mexican directors such as the multi-Academy Award winner [Alejandro González Iñárritu](/Alejandro_Gonz%C3%A1lez_I%C3%B1%C3%A1rritu) (*[Amores perros](/Amores_perros)*, *[Babel](/Babel_(film))*, *[Birdman](/Birdman_(film))*, *The Revenant*), the visionary [Alfonso Cuarón](/Alfonso_Cuar%C3%B3n) (*[Children of Men](/Children_of_Men)*, *[Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban](/Harry_Potter_and_the_Prisoner_of_Azkaban_(film))*, *[Gravity](/Gravity_(2013_film))*, *[Roma](/Roma_(2018_film))*) and the fantastical [Guillermo del Toro](/Guillermo_del_Toro) (*[Pacific Rim](/Pacific_Rim_(film))*, *[Crimson Peak](/Crimson_Peak)*, *[The Shape of Water](/The_Shape_of_Water)*), alongside director [Carlos Carrera](/Carlos_Carrera) (*[The Crime of Father Amaro](/El_crimen_del_Padre_Amaro)*) and screenwriter [Guillermo Arriaga](/Guillermo_Arriaga), stand among the most recognized and influential filmmakers working in contemporary global cinema. Their collective work continues to bring Mexican storytelling to the forefront of the world stage.

### Visual arts

*   See also: [Mexican art](/Mexican_art)

Mexico's commemorative car of the [bicentennial of Mexico](/Celebration_of_Mexican_political_anniversaries_in_2010) during the [Rose Parade](/Rose_Parade) [Pasadena](/Pasadena) (California). January 2010

Post-revolutionary art in [Mexico](/Mexico) found its most potent and expressive voice in the works of a pantheon of renowned artists, who collectively forged a distinct national aesthetic. Iconic figures such as [Frida Kahlo](/Frida_Kahlo), whose deeply personal and symbolic self-portraits continue to captivate; [Diego Rivera](/Diego_Rivera), the monumental figure of Mexican muralism; [José Clemente Orozco](/Jos%C3%A9_Clemente_Orozco), known for his dramatic and often politically charged murals; [Rufino Tamayo](/Rufino_Tamayo), who integrated pre-Columbian forms with modern European styles; [Federico Cantú Garza](/Federico_Cant%C3%BA_Garza), celebrated for his classical yet emotive works; [David Alfaro Siqueiros](/David_Alfaro_Siqueiros), a revolutionary and master of dynamic public art; and [Juan O'Gorman](/Juan_O%27Gorman), an architect and muralist, all contributed to this vibrant artistic period. [Diego Rivera](/Diego_Rivera), arguably the most internationally recognized figure of Mexican muralism, famously painted "Man at the Crossroads" at the [Rockefeller Center](/Rockefeller_Center) in [New York City](/New_York_City). This monumental mural, however, was controversially destroyed the following year due to the inclusion of a portrait of the Russian communist leader [Lenin](/Vladimir_Lenin), highlighting the intense political and ideological clashes of the era, even in the realm of art.

### Architecture

*   Main article: [Architecture of Mexico](/Architecture_of_Mexico)

The artistic relevance and sheer historical significance of many of [Mexico](/Mexico)'s architectural structures are such that entire sections of its prehispanic and colonial cities have been rightfully designated as [World Heritage Sites](/World_Heritage_Site) by [UNESCO](/UNESCO). This prestigious recognition is a testament to the nation's profound cultural legacy. Indeed, [Mexico](/Mexico) holds the distinguished position of having the highest number of sites declared [World Heritage Sites](/World_Heritage_Site) by [UNESCO](/UNESCO) across the entirety of the [Americas](/Americas), underscoring its unparalleled contribution to global architectural and historical patrimony.

### Cuisine

*   Main article: [Mexican cuisine](/Mexican_cuisine)

Mole is the national dish of Mexico

Mexican cuisine, a vibrant and globally celebrated culinary tradition, is a delectable fusion profoundly influenced by both Spanish and indigenous cultures. At its heart lies [Mole](/Mole_(sauce)), a complex and richly flavored sauce, proudly considered the national dish of [Mexico](/Mexico), embodying centuries of culinary evolution. A remarkable legacy of the ancient [Aztecs](/Aztec_Empire) of [Mexico](/Mexico) includes the discovery and cultivation of two globally beloved ingredients: [chocolate](/Chocolate) and [vanilla](/Vanilla). Beyond these, the indigenous peoples of [Mexico](/Mexico) introduced a veritable pantry of staple foods and flavors to the world, including the ubiquitous [corn](/Corn), the versatile [sweet potatoes](/Sweet_potatoes), the essential [tomatoes](/Tomatoes), the tropical [papayas](/Papayas), the fiery chilies, the creamy [avocados](/Avocado), and the succulent [pineapples](/Pineapple). This indigenous bounty forms the backbone of Mexican gastronomy, a testament to the agricultural ingenuity and culinary sophistication of pre-Columbian civilizations.

### Holidays

The [Day of the Dead](/Day_of_the_Dead) (Día de los Muertos) stands as an immensely important and cherished Mexican holiday, observed with deep reverence and vibrant celebration by Mexicans across the nation and beyond. This unique holiday is a profound cultural synthesis, intricately influenced by ancient Mesoamerican ritual traditions, the pervasive European religion of Catholicism, and the broader Spanish culture introduced during the colonial era. The origins of this poignant celebration trace their roots back thousands of years to the indigenous peoples of [Mexico](/Mexico), such as the sophisticated [Aztecs](/Aztec_Empire) and the enigmatic [Toltecs](/Toltec), long before the arrival of Europeans. These ancient civilizations held complex beliefs about death and the afterlife, honoring their ancestors with elaborate ceremonies and offerings, traditions that have evolved and endured to shape the modern [Day of the Dead](/Day_of_the_Dead).

## Religion

*   Main article: [Religion in Mexico](/Religion_in_Mexico)
*   Religion in Mexico (2017)
    *   [Catholic Church](/Catholic_Church) (80.0%)
    *   Other [Christians](/Christianity) (5.00%)
    *   Other religions (3.00%)
    *   Non-religious (11.0%)
    *   Unspecified (1.00%)

[Day of the Dead](/Day_of_the_Dead) celebration

[Mexico](/Mexico) officially operates as a secular state, meaning it has no designated official [religion](/Religion). However, the overwhelming majority of Mexicans, with approximately 80% of the population as of 2017, declare themselves to be [Roman Catholic](/Catholic_Church_in_Mexico). This makes [Mexico](/Mexico) home to the world's second-largest Catholic population, surpassed only by [Brazil](/Brazil). [Mexico](/Mexico) is widely perceived as a deeply observant Catholic society, with most Mexicans tending to hold opinions that are broadly aligned with [Catholic social teaching](/Catholic_social_teaching). The country has historically demonstrated a notable resistance to [Protestant](/Protestant) incursions, a phenomenon partly attributed to the long-standing association of [Protestantism](/Protestantism_in_Mexico) in [Mexico](/Mexico) with the [United States](/United_States). This perceived link often serves to reinforce Catholicism as an integral component of Mexican national identity, making any shift away from it feel like a cultural concession.

The [Constitution of 1917](/Constitution_of_1917), a landmark document forged in the crucible of revolution, imposed significant limitations on the institutional power of the church and, in several instances, codified direct state intrusion into church matters. Under this framework, the government does not provide financial contributions to the church, nor does the church participate in the public education system. Despite this separation, certain religious holidays retain their national significance: [Christmas](/Christmas) is observed as a national holiday, and annually, during both [Easter](/Easter) and [Christmas](/Christmas) periods, all schools in [Mexico](/Mexico), whether public or private, grant their students a well-deserved vacation.

In a significant policy shift in 1992, [Mexico](/Mexico) moved to lift almost all remaining restrictions on religion. This liberalization included granting all religious groups legal status, conceding to them limited property rights, and removing previous restrictions on the number of priests permitted to serve in the country, marking a new era of religious freedom and tolerance.

While the [Catholic Church](/Catholic_Church) remains the overwhelmingly dominant religion in [Mexico](/Mexico), with approximately 80% of the population identifying as Catholic as of 2017, a fascinating counter-current has emerged in recent decades. Movements advocating for the return and revival of indigenous [Mesoamerican religions](/Mesoamerican_religion), such as [Mexicayotl](/Mexicayotl) and [Toltecayotl](/Toltecayotl), have gained traction, reflecting a renewed interest in pre-Columbian spiritual traditions and a reassertion of indigenous cultural identity.

## Diaspora

*   Main article: [Emigration from Mexico](/Emigration_from_Mexico)

A substantial Mexican [diaspora](/Diaspora) exists, most notably concentrated in the [United States](/United_States). Within the U.S., these communities are particularly dense in states like [California](/California) and [Texas](/Texas), with the [Greater Los Angeles](/Greater_Los_Angeles) area serving as a prominent hub for a large Mexican immigrant population, a testament to historical ties and geographical proximity. Beyond the [United States](/United_States), a sizeable Mexican population also resides in [Canada](/Canada), which hosts the next largest contingent of Mexicans abroad. Other countries with significant Mexican communities include [Spain](/Spain), [Guatemala](/Guatemala), and [Germany](/Germany), reflecting diverse migratory patterns driven by economic, social, and historical factors.

